# Code Quality Standards

Always:

- Strong typing
- **Reusable code** — write functions, components, hooks, utils, and
  services that can be used in more than one place without modification;
  prefer small, composable units with clear inputs/outputs over one-off
  implementations
- Clean architecture
- Modular code
- **DRY** — extract shared logic into helpers, utils, or composable
  abstractions; never copy-paste the same block across methods, files, or
  layers

Never:

- Any types
- Inline hacks
- Duplicate code
- One-off code that could be a shared util or component

## Reusable code (global — applies to client/ and server/)

Write code that is meant to be reused, not rewritten:

- **Single responsibility** — each function/component does one thing well
- **Generic where appropriate** — accept params/props instead of hardcoding
  values; avoid coupling to a single page, route, or feature unless
  intentional
- **Composable** — smaller pieces combine into larger ones; don't build
  monoliths that can't be split later
- **Shared by default** — if two features need the same behavior, create one
  shared implementation in the right layer (`client/lib/`, `server/shared/`,
  `components/ui`, module `*.dto.ts` / `*.types.ts`, etc.) rather than two
  parallel copies

Ask before writing: *"Will something else need this later?"* If yes, make
it reusable now.

## DRY (global — applies to client/ and server/)

If the same logic appears more than once anywhere in the codebase, extract
it immediately:

- **Within a file** — private method or module-level helper
- **Across files in one layer** — shared util or composable component/hook
- **Within client or server** — reuse via that app's own shared folders
  (`client/lib/types/`, `server/shared/validation/`, etc.); keep client and
  server types/schemas in their respective folders and aligned with the API
  contract in `17-frontend-integration.mdc`

Public methods and components stay thin: they prepare **what** differs
(content, params, props) and delegate **how** to a single helper.

Never copy-paste an entire function or component body and change one line —
that means a helper is missing.

This applies equally to services, controllers, adapters, React components,
hooks, email templates, error mapping, validation, and styling patterns.

Files should remain:

- Readable
- Maintainable
- Scalable

Use descriptive naming.

Prefer composition over complexity.
